caption: Table 1: A comparison of the trained score of the Brownian motion process.
description: This table compares the root mean squared error (RMSE), training time, and number of epochs for training the score function of a Brownian motion process using two different discretization methods: Fourier basis and landmarks.  The comparison is made for different numbers of basis functions/landmarks (8, 16, 32). The results show the trade-off between accuracy (RMSE), computational cost (Time), and training time (Epochs).

caption: Table 2: Training configurations for learning scores with different numbers of bases
description: This table shows different training configurations used for learning scores with varying numbers of Fourier bases.  It details the input and output dimensions, time embedding dimensions, downsampling and upsampling dimensions, and the activation function used for each configuration.  These configurations were likely experimented with to find optimal settings for different levels of complexity.
